text: A hashtag Felix Jones wanted to get trending.[1]
.party() was a party hosted at PAX that Notch hosted

Reference to Baba Is You, a 2D puzzle game based around forming "rules" with word tiles. One rule is [Object] is you, which makes any object controllable.
This splash is currently the only splash that does not exist in the splashes.txt file. The player's name is entirely capitalized as well.
Prior to 1.18, this splash read "[this splash text has been delayed until part 2]", which referred to this announcement made by Mojang Studios which split Caves & Cliffs into two parts.
"Sugar-free" is frequently used in food-related advertisements and packaging. Before Minecraft 1.9, this splash read "0% sugar!". Additionally, sugar is available as an item.
A reference to some juices that use "100% pure" or a variant thereof as a selling point.[2]
A parody of KFC's secret chicken flavoring recipe containing 11 herbs and spices.

This is a reference to pregnancy: 400,000 minutes is approximately 9 months and 150 BPM is the average fetal heart rate. If BPM is instead interpreted as "blocks per minute", this would equal 60 million, the maximum size of a Java Edition world. However, this appears to just be a coincidence, as the fixed world border was not added until 1.7.2, nearly two years after this splash.
A hyperbole is an exaggeration used to generate emphasis or humor. 150% is, naturally, an exaggeration.
Refers to BASIC. When executed, this line would create an infinite loop, continuously re-executing whatever instruction was on line 10 (usually a PRINT statement).
4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42 are The Numbers that appear all over the television series Lost.
90210 is famous for being the ZIP Code for Beverly Hills, California.
Reference to the "AND THEN A SKELETON POPPED OUT" trollpasta[3]
Changelog in the blog post for snapshot 16w20a contains puns about fixing broken absolute and relative coordinates.
Afraid of the big, black bat!

A quote from The Riddler in the film Batman Forever: "Riddle me this, riddle me that, who's afraid of the big, black bat?" Also, could be a reference to the ender dragon, as this splash was added around the same time.
Age of Wonders is a PC turn-based strategy game. It is often to be compared with "Civilization", which is also a turn-based strategy game.
"All Is Full of Love" is a song by Icelandic singer Björk.
Reference to a tweet by Michael Stoyke teasing the 18w20a snapshot.
Braid is a 2D puzzle-platformer game based on time manipulation.
Limbo is a 2D puzzle-platformer game based on avoiding ingenious traps.
Mount&Blade is a medieval-themed RPG for Microsoft Windows.
PixelJunk Shooter is a 2D shooter that is available only on the PlayStation 3.
Project Zomboid is a zombie apocalypse-themed game.
Super Meat Boy is a 2D platformer game based on difficult levels.

Terraria is a 2D action-adventure, open-world sandbox / platformer game with a similar premise to Minecraft. Terraria features title messages similar to splashes; one of the messages reads "Terraria: Also try Minecraft!".
VVVVVV is a 2D puzzle-platformer game based on gravity manipulation. Both it and Minecraft were included in the Humble Indie Bundle 3.
World of Goo is a 2D physics-based puzzle game.
Amplify and listen to BIPOC voices!
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
An illusion! What are you hiding?

Reference to a World of Warcraft meme (goes together with splash 355). It is also a reference to the 17w16a blog post on minecraft.net for the illusioner addition, saying "An Illusioner! What are you hiding?".[4]
From a quote by the dwarf Gimli in the film The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring: "And my axe!" References the pickaxe, one of the most iconic items in the game.
Any computer is a laptop if you're brave enough!
A riddle, wrapped in a mystery!
From a quote by Winston Churchill; "It is a riddle wrapped in a mystery inside an enigma".
A common marketing claim that is often lampooned.
Similar to "As seen on TV", said at some point in almost every pharmaceutical advertisement.
An autological word is a word that describes itself. Prior to Minecraft 1.0 RC1, this read '"Noun" is an autonym!'.
A reference to the video "Random Changes and Bad Game Design" by the YouTuber _MethodZz_, where he repeatedly uses this phrase while demonstrating several bugs in Java Edition 1.14.
A reference to the "Creeper, aww man" meme, originating from CaptainSparklez' Minecraft parody song, "Revenge".[5]
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
A line from one of Weebl's works, "cup". Predates the addition of bees.
A reference to Bekarton the Gatekeeper, a character in Jeb's game Whispers in Akarra.
A frequently-used catchphrase in car commercials.

"Big Pointy Teeth" is the name of a rabbit in Jeb's game Whispers in Akarra – this is a reference to a quote made by Tim the Enchanter from the movie Monty Python and the Holy Grail describing the Rabbit as a terrible beast with "nasty, big, pointy teeth!"[6]
Refers to a question asked by Steve Allen, "Is it bigger than a breadbox?", during a game of 20 Questions on What's My Line?.
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
Refers to a line in the arcade game Gauntlet.
Line from the song "Low" by Flo Rida, featuring T-Pain.
This splash has two meanings: one related to translation ("pain" is French for "bread"), and one ironic (bread in Minecraft heals the player).
Notch was a big fan of Ray Cokes and used to enjoy it when he was little.
"Bringing home the bacon" is a phrase that, similar to "breadwinner", refers to providing for a group of people or household.
Bob the Angry Flower is a comic strip that has been running since 1992.
A bucket may be filled with lava.
Reference to the nickname given to Rock Lee by Naruto in the Naruto anime and manga.
Name of the Java Edition 1.15 update.
Ceci n'est pas une title screen!

"Ceci n'est pas une" is French for "This is not a"; the phrase refers to The Treachery of Images (La trahison des images), a painting by the Belgian René Magritte, which depicts a pipe with the sentence "Ceci n'est pas une pipe." ("This is not a pipe.") written beneath it. The all-French version of this splash would be "Ceci n'est pas un texte d'accueil!"
The Far Lands were the "limit" of the infinite map, until Notch accidentally fixed them in Beta 1.8. Ironically, this splash was added to the game after the Far Lands were fixed.
A phrase used to imply something is easy, just like how Minecraft is easy to play.

Minecraft is currently closed-source proprietary software, meaning the source code has not been publicly released. Before he sold the game to Microsoft, Notch mentioned this could change "once sales start dying and a minimum time has passed", at which point he would "possibly release it all as public domain".[7]
Cloud computing is the delivery of computing as a service rather than a product.
Latin for "I think, therefore I am." A quote from René Descartes.
Lyrics to "Ice Ice Baby" by American rapper Vanilla Ice.
This splash is stored as "§1C§2o§3l§4o§5r§6m§7a§8t§9i§ac" in splashes.txt; the "§" and the character following are color codes that determine the color of the text following the code.
Referring to goats as well as Goat Simulator.
Both Minecraft and an earlier work of Notch's feature cellular automata; Notch has stated that he is fascinated by it.
Refers to an episode of Homestar Runner.
Cough or sneeze into your elbow!
Coughing or sneezing into your elbow helps to mitigate the spread of germs. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
Refers to a Far Side comic by Gary Larson.
Line from the song "Americano" by "The Brian Setzer Orchestra".[8]
Polish for "Hello, Poland!". Before 1.3.2 Pre-release, the splash was "Cześć Polska".
Déjà vu is the experience of feeling sure that one has already witnessed or experienced a current situation.
Part of the Minecraft terms and conditions;[9] referred to as "The one major rule" by Notch.
Do you want to join my server?
Relates to people in the community asking others to join their multiplayer servers.
Refers to a move that can be performed by the Arwing in Star Fox games. In Star Fox 64, the humorous way in which Peppy Hare said "Do a barrel roll!" led to the creation of a meme.
A double negative is where two forms of negation are used in the same sentence. This sentence itself uses double negatives.

Relates to the numerous "clones" of Minecraft, such as Total Miner: Forge, and perhaps an ironic reference to the fact that Minecraft conceptually is itself a "clone" of Infiniminer, and therefore "clones" might not be negative remakes of other games.
Avocados are poisonous to birds. This splash predates the parrot mob (a similar situation happened regarding music and axolotls). Also, avocados are not available in Minecraft.

Chocolate is poisonous to birds, so feeding a cookie to an in-game parrot mob kills it instantly.
This splash was added during the same development updates as the parrot mob.
Don't look directly at the bugs!
Avoiding contact with your face can help mitigate the spread of germs. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
"Don’t Worry, Be Happy" is a song by American jazz artist Bobby McFerrin.
"doot-doot, thank mr skeltal" is a phrase related to the "skull trumpet" meme.[10][11] The splash was added at the time skeleton horses were added to the game.
A common screen rendering technique that Minecraft uses.
Refers to the horror manga short story The Enigma of Amigara Fault.
DungeonQuest is a board game whose gameplay relies on the players creating the playing board by randomly selecting tiles and placing them on a grid.

Edit is a name!‌[JE only]
Edit is a name‌[BE only]
Edit is Scandinavian derivative of the English name Edith.
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
Refers to the Star Trek saying "Engage!" by Jean-Luc Picard, a signal to act on previously given orders.
The motto of the indie game dev group HBGames, which Felix Jones added as a splash to pay homage.[12][13]
Title of a piece by Norwegian electronic music duo Röyksopp.
Minecraft worlds are mostly made up of one of the simplest forms of Euclidean geometry, the cube. The splash contains a typo.[14]
"Leif" is a Scandinavian term that means "beloved."
Reference to the beloved creeper in the game.
Often happened accidentally before sneaking was implemented.
Said to Sheriff Woody by Buzz Lightyear in the 1995 film Toy Story, "This isn't flying, this is falling with style!". Added soon after elytra were added to the game.
Often an advertising point on food, directed at people attempting to lose or keep from gaining weight.
A reference to the fact that Minecraft has finally left Beta. While it may have been "officially released", it is (in reality) far from "complete" and continually being developed.[15]
Ladders were added to the game in Infdev.
"Finger-lickin' good" is a slogan of KFC.
Referring to the flashing of the splash text itself.
Line from the song "Just Don't Give" by Eminem.

A reference to Bobo, a children's comic created by Swedish cartoonist Lars Mortimer, in which the title character had a magical spyglass called the Flaxkikare, which can be translated to English as "lucky spyglass" or "happiness/flash telescope".

Flower forest TM perfume
‌[upcoming: JE 1.19 & BE 1.19.0]
Fnord is the typographic representation of disinformation or irrelevant information.
A reference to the mission "Wrong Side Of The Tracks" in Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas.
Free dental is often a talking point about a job advertisement, and is similar to "As seen on TV".
Reference to farm animals (particularly chickens) being raised "free-range," with space to roam freely without cages.
Södermalm is the district in Stockholm where Mojang Studios' offices are located.[16]

Part of a quote from Dr. David Bowman ("The thing's hollow—it goes on forever—and—oh my God—it's full of stars!") and his last line before being pulled through the monolith, from the novel 2001: A Space Odyssey (while often attributed to the film of the same name, the line does not actually appear on-screen until its sequel, 2010: The Year We Make Contact). However, Minecraft is full of stars. They are square pixels on the screen that appear at nighttime.
A repeated lyric in a vocal sample in the Fatboy Slim song "The Rockafeller Skank". The sample comes from the beginning of the song "Vinyl Dog Vibe" by Vinyl Dogs.

(Obfuscated) This splash is stored as "§kFUNKY LOL" in splashes.txt; as with the "Colormatic" splash, the "§k" is a formatting code, but instead of changing the color of the following text, the code obfuscates the text, replacing it with random, rapidly-changing characters.
Gamers unite – separately in your own homes!
Playing multiplayer games separately helps maintain social distancing. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
Gargamel is the main antagonist of The Smurfs.
Reference to a famous line from the film Predator, as well as the addition of copper in 1.17.
"Potato chips", spelled phonetically using obscure rules of English pronunciation.[17]
A reference to the command /give. If minecraft:hugs were an item, this would give all players 64 hugs.
Refers to the internet tribute for Terry Pratchett, where the text "X-Clacks-Overhead: GNU Terry Pratchett" is added to the headers of websites.[18]
It is recommended that people visit the dentist at least twice a year.
A past-tense misspelling of Google Analytics, a service that provides statistics about visitors to a website.
Based on an old joke where one person grabs someone's nose, then moves their hand away with their own thumb through the middle of their two first fingers.
A common abbreviation for "Game of the Year". Minecraft has been nominated — and voted — Game of the Year by a number of gaming magazines and news sites.
A reference to the webcomic "The Order of the Stick", in which Haley Starshine has a long-concealed crush on Elan and eventually starts a relationship with him.
Hampster Dance is one of the oldest internet memes.

A contentious scene in Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope. In the original version of the film, Han Solo pulls out his blaster and shoots Greedo before he knows it. In the special edition, Greedo shoots and misses, followed by Han shooting him. This was one of many changes to the film that angered fans. In their plight, they adopted the phrase 'Han shot first!'.
Hang out with your friends online!
Spending time with friends online rather than in person helps promote social distancing. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
This splash predates the creation of Herobrine (the story of which was posted no earlier than the Alpha v1.0.16_02 update) and therefore has nothing to do with it.

Minecraft is among the most popular topics on YouTube, having recieved over one trillion views.[19] Notch's channel, which no longer has content, received over a million views, 33 million video views, and has 91,500+ subscribers. User-created tutorial and demonstration videos, "Let's Play" series, Machinimas, and various other videos are also common. Prior to Alpha v1.0.0(?), this read "700+ hits on YouTube!".

A "Homeomorphism" is a mathematical property indicating that there is a continual topological mapping between two objects; in layman's terms, there exists a way to deform one into the other without cutting or gluing. A "3-sphere" is a sphere in 3 dimensions, or the set of points equidistant from a given center in 4-space, a higher-dimensional analog of the "2-sphere" (what is thought of as an ordinary Sphere.) Possibly a reference to the Poincaré conjecture.

Honey, I grew the bees!‌[JE only]
Honey, I grew the bees‌[BE only]
Reference to the 1989 film Honey, I Shrunk the Kids, as well as the mob added in 1.15.
Another reference to Honey, I Shrunk the Kids, as well as the ability to wax copper blocks.
A reference to a comment on Reddit about villager sounds.

Ancient Domains of Mystery is an old, but popular and unique rogue-like game, featuring a world made completely of ASCII characters for graphics, dungeons (random and infinite), and monsters, but also many (optional) storylines that help hold all the features together to stop it from becoming boring.
I see your vocabulary has improved!
A reference to "Lands of Lore 2", a 1997 game by Westwood Studios.[20]
The no-clip command for Doom, which allows flying and passing through walls. Predates the addition of Spectator Mode.
if not ok then return end
This is Lua script code for exiting a function if the variable "ok" is false or unset.
Indev was the second major version of Minecraft, after Classic. It was succeeded by Infdev.
Minecraft was a game developed independently.
A slogan referring to the fact that keeping information contained tends to be more difficult than allowing it to disseminate.
Iron, gold, copper and Netherite ingots are obtainable in the game.
This splash was added around the time when multiplayer was reintroduced to the game.
In case it isn't obvious, foxes aren't players.
Reference to the Mojira bug tracker ticket MC-166292, in which foxes are referred to as players upon teleporting after eating chorus fruit.
Reference to @zarawesome's tweet in which it's said that Minecraft comes from space.
Line from the song "Crazy Little Thing Called Love" by the band Queen.
Prior to Minecraft Java Edition 1.0.0 RC1, this read "When it's finished!".
Prior to Minecraft 1.0.0 RC1, this splash read "Coming soon!".
Swedish for "I know a bot". Refers to the first line of the song "Boten Anna" by the Swedish dance artist, Basshunter.

Support for Java 5 was dropped in Minecraft 1.6.1. Before 1.7.2, this splash read "Almost java 6!". Before 1.12, this splash read "Now Java 6!". Before 1.17, this splash read "Now Java 8!". Before 1.18, this splash read "Now Java 16!". This splash is one of three splashes that were changed more than once, and the only one that has been changed five times.
Referring to Java Edition. Also a portmanteau of "Java Edition" and "Delicious".
Referring to Mojang employee Jens Bergensten having long, red hair.
May refer to Canadian electronic music composer deadmau5, whose real name is Joel Zimmerman.
Jump up, jump up, and get down!
"Jump Around" by American hip-hop group "House of Pain".
Refers to the Japanese anime film Akira.

Minecraft is playable with a keyboard. This splash text still appears in versions that do not contain keyboard support, such as Legacy Console Edition. This issue was fixed in the New Nintendo 3DS Edition only, as the splash text was replaced with “Touch Compatible!” Which, this version, indeed, is touch compatible.
A reference to the scene in Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan when Captain Kirk screams Khan's name.
Lyrics from the song "Root Down" by American hip-hop band "Beastie Boys".

It may be a possible reference to a quote from Wurm Online, wherein Notch states that "we will never add dragons". Dragons were eventually added, however. The same thing happened in Minecraft with the addition of the ender dragon in Beta 1.9 Prerelease 4. Before RC1, this splash read "Absolutely dragon free!".
Lemmings is a game which also features mining, digging and blowing things up.
A reference to the lyrics from "Purple Haze" by American guitarist Jimi Hendrix.

Leet is a type of symbolic spelling in which letters are replaced by lookalike numbers, punctuation, other symbols, and even characters from other languages. For example, "hello" written as "|-|3110".

The theoretical maximum size of the map in Minecraft is roughly eight times the total surface area of the Earth. However, technical restrictions mean that the actual maximum size is much smaller, though still larger than the Earth.
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement (& extensible to other equality movements, e.g. trans rights).
May be a reference to the urban legend that Donald Duck was illegal in Finland. May also be a reference to the fact that the sale of snus (Swedish tobacco) is illegal in Finland.

"Lennart" is a Swedish variant of the name "Leonard". This is Java code (the programming language that Minecraft is written in) that creates a new instance of "Lennart", named "lennart", of type "Lennart".
Probably a reference to Bob the Angry Flower.
A reference to a typo Notch made while working on Wurm Online.
A common example of business speak.
Lives in a pineapple under the sea!
Part of the opening line of the theme song for the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants.
Minecraft is livestreamed on many platforms.
Look mum, I’m in a splash!
A reference to American late-night host Stephen Colbert's favorite word "truthiness".
Macroscopic is a word that means "visible," the way splash texts are.
Jeb became the lead Minecraft developer once Notch stepped down from developing it in 2011. This splash was added by Notch.[21]
A parody of the well-known phrase found attached to imported goods: "Made in _" (Country), based on Mojang being centered in Sweden.
Make me a table, a funky table!
Line from the song "Funkhauser" by Hard 'n Phirm.
Reference to the level MAP11 in the game Doom II: Hell on Earth, which is called both "Circle of Death" and "O' of Destruction!" in-game.
May refer to Team America: World Police, in which Matt Damon is a simpleton who can say only his name.
A food allergen warning, as well as a play on developer and current tech lead of Java Edition, slicedlime.

The Menger sponge is a fractal object constructed by dividing a cube into 27 smaller cubes and removing the smaller center cube from each of the larger cube's six faces and the smaller cube in the larger cube's center, and repeating this operation for each remaining smaller cube, and then for each of the even smaller cubes, and so on. A Menger sponge can be exactly represented in Minecraft up to the fifth iteration. A Menger sponge world can be found in the 2020 April Fools snapshot 20w14∞.
Line from the song "Peaches" by The Presidents of the United States of America
Minecraft Java Edition presents: Disgusting Bugs
Pun on the word "Bugs"; referring to both software bugs, and actual living bugs. It is also a reference to the 1.15 Pre-Release article.
A pun on 'miners' being a homophone of 'minors', and the game is commonly played among children.
Prior to 1.16 Pre-release 3, this splash read, "Sexy!"
Aggressive mobs can attack one another if the player can get one mob to accidentally attack another through a mechanic called Monster Infighting.
Most of today's video games, including Minecraft, are visually based on polygons.

In Indev and Infdev, this splash originally read "More than 5000 sold!". In Alpha v1.0.0, it was changed to read "More than 25000 sold!", and between Alpha v1.0.12 and Alpha v1.0.14, it was changed to the current splash, making it one of three splashes to be changed more than once.
The large majority of Minecraft's music was composed by C418.
Refers to five tracks composed by Lena Raine for the Nether Update.
Aiur is the homeworld of the protoss in the StarCraft video game series. The phrase is typically said by Protoss Zealots.
Digging directly down is never recommended, since there could be a long drop, a dungeon, mobs or lava below the player.
A reference to the announcement video for the Minecraft Live 2021 vote, in which Jens Bergensten voiced the line, and subsequently went viral.

Spock is a popular Star Trek character. Prior to 1.8.5, this splash read "Cooler than Spock!". Leonard Nimoy, who played Spock, died on February 27, 2015, one week after the release of 1.8.3 and 84 days before the text was changed in Spock's favor.
As Minecraft is a sandbox game, there is no actual storyline to follow; the game's appeal instead lies in emergent gameplay.
Steam is an online service used to distribute many Indie games, as well as Valve games. Minecraft is not sold via Steam, but only on the Minecraft website. However, two spin-offs released on Steam.
A reference to a Twitter user who sent pictures of cats to Mojang every day until stained glass was added to Minecraft. There are 32 stained glass blocks.
Minecraft had a 3D Anaglyph mode until 17w43a. Even though 3D Anaglyph was removed in 17w43a, the splash still exists. Additionally, Minecraft takes place in a 3D world.

Another technology used by Minecraft. Prior to 1.17 (21w10a), this read "OpenGL 2.1 (if supported)!". Prior to 1.8 (14w06a), this read "Open GL 1.2!". Prior to Minecraft 1.0 RC1, this read "OpenGL 1.1!". This splash is one of three that have been changed more than once, and one of two that has been changed three times.

These characters are not part of the standard 26-character Latin alphabet, but are used in the Swedish alphabet (many Scandinavian languages use such extended versions of the Latin alphabet). Minecraft now supports these characters in in-game input fields.
Since the release of Minecraft, there have been many updates through subsequent updates that have added new features to the game.
Difficulty may be set to Peaceful, Easy, Normal, or Hard.
Now you are thinking with pistons!
Refers to pistons. Also a parody of a catchphrase associated with Portal: "Now you're thinking with portals!"

The P versus NP problem is widely considered the most important unsolved problem in computer science. In layman's terms, the problem asks if certain problems are inherently much more difficult than others, measured by the computation time needed to solve them.
Zombified Piglins, formerly known as Zombie Pigmen, may be found in the Nether.
When read aloud, "Oh, I see you ate one, too." Most likely a reference to the Van Halen album "OU812", but may also be a reference to Text messaging.
One day, somewhere in the future, my work will be quoted!
The slogan of the UK-based PC gaming blog Rock, Paper, Shotgun.[22]
Head of the family from the animated TV show Family Guy.
Refers to the YouTuber and Twitch streamer Ph1lza (Phil Watson). He is best known for losing his record breaking hardcore world after surviving for over five years (2014 to 2019).
The final map of Doom's first episode.

May be a reference to the act of "pinging" or mentioning someone on Discord, playing the notification sound. May also be a reference to Finn the Human, a protagonist of the animated series Adventure Time.
Everything in Minecraft is made out of pixels.
A snowclone meme originating from a post on the blog "Hyperbole and a Half", which contained an image with the phrase "Clean ALL the things!".[23]
Saplings become trees after a certain amount of time.
Keyboard Cat is an internet meme wherein after someone makes an embarrassing mistake a cat is shown playing a keyboard, frequently accompanied by the phrase "play him off, keyboard cat".
Play Minecraft, Watch Topgear, Get Pig!

Added during the yearly LRR Desert Bus charity drive.
References Top Gear, a popular British motoring show.

Alpha v1.2.3
[is this the correct version?]
Shortened form of "please retweet", in relation to Twitter.
References how people on Twitter often request for a Mojangsta to reply to their tweet, often of a bug report, feature request, or question.
It is recommended to purchase necessities before and during a crisis, but as a courtesy, leaving enough for others is strongly encouraged. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
"Pumpakungen" is Swedish for "(the) pumpkin king". It is intentionally misspelt as "pumpa kungen" as a joke, as it can be read as "pump the king".[24]
Pumpkins are wearable as helmets in Minecraft.
While not strictly necessary, it is nearly impossible to start a new world without collecting wood, which, lacking tools, must be done by punching it.
Put a little fence around it!
Refers to the "Catbug" episode of the YouTube series Bravest Warriors.
Said by Arnold Schwarzenegger in the Christmas movie Jingle All the Way.
Different splash texts appear randomly, just like this one.
In snapshot 16w21a, there was a graphical bug making lava appear blood-red, and when that was fixed, Searge compared lava to molten cheese and blood.[25]
Edsbyn is a village in Sweden with around 4000 residents; Notch lived in Edsbyn for the first years of his life.
Refers to a running gag during loading processes in many games of The Sims and Spore series by Maxis, and the fictional videogame SBURB from Homestuck.
Pigs can be ridden with a saddle.
Refers to the arcade game Altered Beast.
Rita is the new top dog!
Refers to an old Australian TV show, Prisoner.
Searge posted this on Twitter, in regards to the lava texture being blood-red in 16w21a.[26]
Refers to the arcade game Sinistar, which includes the lines "Beware, I live!", "I hunger, coward!", "Run! Run! Run!", "Beware, coward!", "I hunger!", and "Run, coward!".
Referring to former Mojang employee Ryan Holtz having long, brown hair.
See you next Friday or so!
The release day (Friday, November 18, 2011) of the full release of Minecraft (1.0.0) during MineCon.
Before Minecraft went Beta, updates were released weekly, every Friday. Notch called these updates "Seecret Friday updates".
Shopping in place of those with compromised or weak immune systems, especially relatives over 60, helps to keep them safe from disease. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
Should not be played while driving

The August 8, 2016 update[27] to the game Pokémon GO included a new warning to players traveling above a certain speed: "You're going too fast! Pokémon GO should not be played while driving." Additionally, Minecraft or any other mobile game should never be played while driving or operating machinery.

Shriek like a Sculk Shrieker!
‌[upcoming: JE 1.19 & BE 1.19.0]
A reference to the sculk shrieker.
Minecraft was, at the time this splash was created, a one-player game.

Portals to the Nether (but not the End) take a few seconds to activate, although in Creative mode, they are instant. In addition, it is satire on many claims about cleaning products i.e. "Fast acting stain remover" or "Fast acting solvent".
Washing hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds is one of the most effective ways to kill harmful bacteria and viruses. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
"So Fresh, So Clean" is a song by American hip-hop duo Outkast.
Reference to a World of Warcraft meme (goes together with splash 354).
So sweet, like a nice bon bon!
Refers to a line in the song "Body Movin'" by American hip-hop group the Beastie Boys.
Speak OUT against injustice and UP for equality!
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement (& extensible to other equality movements, e.g. trans rights).
There are a lot of spiders in Minecraft during the night.
Mathematical confession using imaginary numbers. Imaginary numbers, including sqrt(-1) are represented by the mathematical constant i, so this phrase translates to "i love you".
A quote from Impossible Mission, a game for the Commodore 64.
Stand up for equality in your community!
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement (& extensible to other equality movements, e.g. trans rights).
A quote from Elder Deckard Cain from the Diablo series.
Stay home and play video games!
Stop being reasonable, this is the Internet!
Searge posted this quote on Twitter.[28]
A phrase from the song "U Can't Touch This" by MC Hammer.
Line from the song "Burning Down the House" by the band Talking Heads.

A term that flourished in the Romance period, used to describe a feeling of simultaneous wonder and terror at natural phenomena- quite apt for many a player's experience of the game. (Additionally, the German Romance painter Caspar David Friedrich's "Wanderer Above the Sea of Fog", frequently cited as a prototypical example of the sublime in art, is the source for an in-game painting.)
The famous song from Disney's Mary Poppins. Before Minecraft RC1, it read "Superfragilisticexpialidocious!"; Notch hinted it may have been a hidden message.[29]
Support the BIPOC community and creators!
Statement in support of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
Continued patronage is essential in order for most small businesses to remain open during challenging times. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
Survival was once the only given objective in the game, although more objectives were added with the inclusion of achievements, then advancements.
A synecdoche (Greek for "simultaneous understanding") is a figure of speech where an object or concept is represented by a part or subconcept.
Take an eggbeater and beat it against a skillet!
Line from the song "Funkhauser" by Hard 'n Phirm.
Take the elevator to the mezzanine!
Line from the song "Super Bon Bon" by Soul Coughing.
Minecraft was made with technology. Also a possible reference to a Daft Punk song, Technologic.
Refers to the Japanese anime film Akira.
In Beta 1.9 Prerelease, all villagers had the name "TESTIFICATE" over their head.
Most likely a reference to So Long, and Thanks for All the Fish from The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy.
Famous quote from Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope. The full quote is "That's no moon, it's a space station!". Prior to Minecraft 1.0 RC1, this splash read "That's not a moon!".
A reference to British television show That Mitchell and Webb Look.
A 1920s slang phrase of unknown etymology, though it possibly originated in Britain. Predates the addition of bees.

"The […] is a spy!" is a common phrase used in Team Fortress 2 to warn other players of enemy spies; the Spy is a class that is able to disguise as the enemy team and kill them from behind, which creepers tend to do.
The cutest predator you'll ever meet!
Referring to axolotls, and the advancement "The Cutest Predator" that you get by catching an axolotl in a bucket.
A common phrase, meaning that there are few limits to projects. Also, no blocks can be placed above the map height.
Reference to the Living systems theory.
Reference to a tweet by former U.S. President Donald Trump whose misspelling ("Despite the constant negative press Covfefe") went viral[30] during the week of the release of 1.12.

From an October 6, 2015, tweet by Jens Bergensten: "I didn't want a hypetrain but there's no stopping "Trollmaso", right? =) Yes, new dramatic feature, likely out in the next snapshot."[31] "Trollmaso" refers to the Twitter account @trollmasso, active since August 2015, whose name "Trollmasso ChiChi" was a play on former Pocket Edition developer Tommaso Checchi. Jeb was referring to elytra in that tweet.
Realms is a server-hosting service run by Mojang.
A common cliché stock phrase usually used by villains and godly figures in works of fantasy. It is mainly employed at the final battle of the game.
This message will never appear on the splash screen, isn't that weird?

This is the first splash that doesn't end with an exclamation point (!), other than the special "missingno" splash. As its text implies, the splash is never displayed in Java Edition (but displays in other editions).
This text is hard to read if you play the game at the default resolution, but at 1080p it's fine!
The splash text scales to fit, making this particular splash difficult to read at lower resolutions.
This parrot is no more! It has ceased to be!
Reference to the "Dead Parrot sketch" from Monty Python's Flying Circus.

Alias for highcolor (16-bit), which can represent up to 65,536 colors, on a Macintosh. Minecraft uses 32-bit colors (24 bits for color and 8 bits for opacity), which can represent around 16.7 million colors (16,777,216) with each color having 256 opacity values.
Refers to the "Catbug" episode of the YouTube series "Bravest Warriors".
Throw yourself at the ground and miss

From the Douglas Adams book Life, the Universe and Everything: "'The Guide says there is an art to flying', said Ford, 'or rather a knack. The knack lies in learning how to throw yourself at the ground and miss.'" This splash was added shortly after elytra were added.
A phrase commonly said by comedians at the end of their performances. Other variations are "Tip your waitress!" or "Try the veal!".[32]
Tougher than diamonds, rich like cream!
Line from the song "The Power of Love" by Huey Lewis and the News. May also a reference of the film Back to the Future.
A commonly-used phrase in medicine advertising.
Lyrics from the song "The Trial" by British progressive rock band Pink Floyd.
Notch often tweeted about Minecraft on his Twitter feed, as do many other people still.
Turing completeness is a term used in computer science for machines and programming languages that are able to perform all operations of a Turing machine. The redstone mechanism is one of them.

Refers to Tyrion Lannister, the dwarf from the George R. R. Martin book A Dance With Dragons, in which he is forced to watch fellow dwarves belittled in a mock pig joust. Minecraft allows the player to ride pigs and perform such jousts. Before Minecraft 1.0 RC1, this splash read "Tyrian would love it!".
Literally "a stick" in French, a Baguette is a kind of bread. Minecraft also features bread and sticks. This could also be a reference to the Flight of the Conchords song "Foux Du Fafa".
A joke on the fact that "inflammable" is often mistaken to mean "not flammable" due to the "in-" prefix.
If the game is unmodded, then it is called "vanilla". This splash can still appear if mods are installed.
Verlet integration is a technique often used to calculate trajectories of particles. It contains a typo.[33]
A reference to a Comedy routine on Russell Howard's Good News done by Hannibal Buress, where he states "I'm very influential in my circle."[34][35]
Net neutrality is a principle that advocates no restrictions by internet service providers or governments on consumers' access to networks that participate in the internet.
Warning! A huge battleship "STEVE" is approaching fast!

Refers to the shoot'em up arcade game Darius Gaiden, where the message is displayed before encountering a boss. In the splash, the word "STEVE" is used as a placeholder for the name of the boss in the game.
Washing hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds is one of the most effective ways to kill harmful bacteria and viruses. Related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
A glass bottle can be filled with water to become a water bottle.
The boss quote from Altered Beast. The capitalization of "Doom" also hints at it being a reference to the game, Doom.

Reference to Dinnerbone being killed by MindCrack member Docm77 during the first episode of MindCrack UHC Season 11,[36][37] based on Looney Tunes character Bugs Bunny, who commonly greeted people by saying "What's up, Doc?"
Where there is not light, there can spider!
One of Ryan Holtz's "personal memes". According to a forum post on Mame World,[38] the phrase was "said by a mutual friend, drunk beyond belief, who had never played Minecraft."

Who let the frogs out?
‌[upcoming: JE 1.19 & BE 1.19.0]
A reference to the game Temple Run.

Facepunch was a game forum. It has since shut down, but this splash is still in the game. Facepunch is also the developer of Garry's Mod, another sandbox game (which also happens to have a "Minecraftity" texturizing option).
Reddit is a popular online news and entertainment site driven by user-submitted content.
A reference to 2 Player Productions, the company behind Minecraft: The Story of Mojang.
TIGSource is an indie game development forum where Notch originally posted Minecraft.[39]
World of Minecraft is yet another popular Minecraft forum.
A reference to a popular image macro series using an image of Bill O'Reilly, with a misunderstanding of a standard occurrence followed by "you can't explain that!".[40]
The August 8, 2016, update[27] to the game Pokémon GO included a new warning to players traveling above a certain speed: "You're going too fast! Pokémon GO should not be played while driving."
You've got a brand new key!
Refers to the song "Brand New Key" by American folk singer Melanie.
Related to the addition of Zoglins in 1.16.
Russian for "Hello, Russia!". According to Russian punctuation rules, there must be a comma after the word "Привет".
Chinese Simplified for "Hello, China!". Actually, there must be a comma after the character "好".
A reference to the port of Java Edition features into Bedrock Edition, implementing them through gradual updates.
All flowers can be crafted into dyes, while grass remains a mundane junk item.
Implementation of dynamic lighting and/or sunlight shading.
Bedrock Edition was written in C++.
Bedrock Edition runs on OpenGL ES.
A variation of the original splash "Haha, LOL!". Lel is a common phonetic variation on the word lol, originating in the practice of substituting random vowels when using the acronym.[41]
Bedrock Edition was, at the time, an independently developed game.
A reference to a common typo when typing in several !s.

A reference to Minecraft's infinite terrain. However, at the time of addition, infinite terrain had not yet been implemented in Bedrock Edition.

Probably in reference to Half-Life 2 Episode 3, which was announced, but doesn't actually exist.
A common marketing term. Additionally, sugar is available as an item.

Team Mystic is one of the teams that can be joined in Pokémon Go.

Refers to a memetic audio clip which, due to poor recording quality, sounds like "yanny" to some listeners and "laurel" to others.

Refers to a simple game in which the floor is imagined as lava and players must seek higher ground.
"<player> discovered floor was lava" is a death message due to players walking on magma blocks.

A portmanteau of panda and pandemonium. Additionally, a free Minecraft map with the same name was added to the marketplace in the same update.

texts.text: This article is about the message on the menu screen. For information shown when loading worlds, see Loading tips. For the potion, see Splash Potion.

Splash texts are the yellow lines of text on the title screen. They are randomly chosen from the list below and often feature references to popular culture (e.g. websites, quotes and video games). The splash pulsates on the title screen twice per second.

Splash texts are not translated and appear the same regardless of the language setting chosen. In Java Edition, the splashes are defined in a plain-text file within the minecraft.jar file (specifically, in version.jar/assets/minecraft/texts/splashes.txt). In Bedrock Edition, the splashes are defined in a .json file. Splashes can be modified by editing the splashes.txt file via a resource pack.

Note: the current versions of all splashes here are documented above; they do not need descriptions or explanations in this section.

When a splash is removed, the line it occupied in splashes.txt / splashes.json is deleted, meaning the line number of all subsequent splashes lowers by one.
Splashes have been in Minecraft since Indev, with new ones regularly added, usually as part of major releases. Prior to Alpha v1.0.14, splashes were stored in an array of strings in the source code.
